occurrences.line_text: Against foule feends to aide vs millitant?
But as a man, whom hellish feends haue frayd,
Where companing with feends and filthy Sprights,
Whose hideous shapes were like to feends of hell,
Th'infernall feends with it he can asswage,
As one with vew of ghastly feends affright:
For fear the cruell Feends should thee vnwares deuowre.
Nath'lesse those feends may not their worke forbeare,
The feends do quake, when any him to them does name.
With which the stubborn feends he to his seruice bound.
And many dreadfull feends hath pointed to her gard.
But like as one, whom feends had made affrayd,
And sacrifizeth to th'infernall feends.
Was crackt in twaine, but by his foolish feere
In stead thereof he kist her wearie feet,
And at her feet the Lyon watch doth keepe:
All bare through peoples feet, which thither traueiled.
And vnderneath their feet, all scattered lay
And with their horned feet do weare the ground,
And vnderneath his filthy feet did tread
Whiles yet his feeble feet for faintnesse reeld,
Both feet and face one way are wont to lead.
Or free his feet, that in the myre sticke fast?
Whereon thy innocent feet doe euer tread,
Or doen thy feeble feet vnweeting hither stray?
And euer when his feet encombred were,
His nigh forwearied feeble feet did slide,
And at his feet their laurell boughes did throw.
And all the floore was vnderneath their feet
Espye a traueiler with feet surbet,
On goodly courser thundring with his feet,
Who suffred not his wandring feet to slide.
And both his feet in fetters to an yron racke.
Whose flying feet so fast their way applyde,
And at their feet her selfe most humbly feld,
His feeble feet directed to the cry;
That vnderneath his feet soone made a purple plesh.
Who wandring through the world with wearie feet,
Their feet vnshod, their bodies wrapt in rags,
Ne scarse his feet on ground were seene to tred;
So vnderneath her feet their swords they mard,
Their tender feet vpon the stony ground:
Thicke forest, was bescratcht, & both his feet nigh lame.
Yet flyes away of her owne feet affeard,
His nimble feet to her conceiued feare,
And to her feet betooke her doubtfull sickernesse.
Whose trampling feet vpon the hollow lay
That can withhold her wilfull wandring feet;
And with their horned feet the greene grasse wore,
His nimble feet, as treading still on thorne:
And now so fast his feet he did apply,
And vnderneath his feet was written thus,
And with her feeble feet did moue a comely pace.
And as her eares so eke her feet were odde,
There she alighting, fell before her feet,
He her beholding, at her feet downe fell,
I count as naught, and tread downe vnder feet,
I spyde, where at the Idoles feet apart
Vnder the which, her feet appeared plaine,
Her siluer feet, faire washt against this day:
Or vnder his fierce horses feet haue borne
Whylest kings and kesars at her feet did them prostrate.
But at her feet her sword was likewise layde,
And round about, before her feet there sate
To faire Irena, at her feet did fall,
Before his feet her selfe she did proiect,
On her faire feet by his horse side did pas
Him seem'd his feet did fly, and in their speed delight.
And falling lowly at his feet, her bowd
His feete all bare, his beard all hoarie gray,
Lo vnderneath her scornefull feete, was layne
Do kisse her feete, and fawne on her with count'nance faine.
And eke her feete most monstrous were in sight;
One of his grasping feete, him to defend thereby.
That from his head no place appeared to his feete.
But prickt so fiers, that vnderneath his feete
Where at his feete, with sorrowfull demaine
His fomy steed, whose fierie feete did burne
Her fearfull feete towards the bowre she moued;
Hast drest my sinfull wounds? I kisse thy blessed feete.
Vpon his hands and feete he crept full light,
He ran as fast, as both his feete could beare,
When her weake feete could scarcely her sustaine,
The other downe vnder their horses feete,
I follow here the footing of thy feete,
And rudely tumbling downe vnder his horse feete fell.
To which I boldly came vpon my feeble feete.
With winged feete, as nimble as the winde;
And both her feete and legs together twyned
With golden hands and siluer feete beside,
And kneeling at his feete submissiuely.
And eke her feete, those feete of siluer trye,
And eke her feete, those feete of siluer trye,
So backe againe they homeward turnd their feete.
And at her feete a Crocodile was rold,
Vnder the Idols feete in fearelesse bowre,
Him selfe before her feete he lowly threw,
That vnder Isis feete doth sleepe for euer:
Fast did they fly, as them their feete could beare,
Whylest vnderneath her feete, there as she sate,
As fast as feete could carry them away;
Before his feete, in all that peoples sight;
Her Lions clawes he from her feete away did wipe.
Their hearts were sicke, their sides were sore, their feete were
Vpon the ground with feeble feete he trode,
Him often scourg'd, and forst his feete to fynd:
Downe on his golden feete he often gazed,
And many feete fast thumping th'hollow ground,
And vnderneath thy feete to place her prayse;
Before the feete of the faire Pastorell;
Tho rearing vp his former feete on hight,
Whom he had feignd th'abuser of my loue to bee.
And in their foolish fancie feigne thee blind,
Whose semblance she did carrie vnder feigned hew.
Forthwith he runnes with feigned faithfull hast
Her seeming dead he found with feigned feare,
For feare as seemd, or for some feigned losse;
A mad man, or that feigned mad to bee,
Let vs in feigned armes our selues disguize,
That feigning dreame, and that faire-forged Spright
Who feigning then in euery limbe to quake,
And in her feigning fancie did pourtray
Feigning full many a fond excuse to prate,
So forth they rode, he feining seemely merth,
So mischief fel vpon the meaners crowne;
Her teeth out of her rotten gummes were feld,
And him so strongly stroke, that to the ground him feld.
And at their feet her selfe most humbly feld,
And high aduaunced crests downe meekely feld,
Their groues he feld, their gardins did deface,
I saw a Saxon Virgin, the which feld
Yet mindfull how he late by one was feld,
Was with the force nigh feld whilst his right foot did slyde.
So these two champions to the ground were feld,
And hauing me all wearie earst, downe feld,
Of butchers balefull hand to ground is feld,
And grudged at the great felicitie
And vowed foe of my felicitie;
Worthy of heauen and hye felicitie,
And raigned long in great felicitie,
With high renowme, and great felicitie?
So life is losse, and death felicitie.
Their goodly meriment, and gay felicitie.
Might else haue with felicitie bene crowned:
And wish my lot were plast in such felicitie.
Did runne about, and their felicities
In kingdome, but not in felicity;
Sporting himselfe in safe felicity:
As seeming plast in sole felicity:
Enuying my too great felicity,
And in the midst of her felicity,
And ioyed long in close felicity:
Assure your selfe, it fell not all to ground;
Now like a foxe, now like a dragon fell,
Soone meete they both, both fell and furious,
My dearest Lord fell from high honours staire,
With pittie calmd, downe fell his angry mood.
Who told her all that fell in iourney as she went.
Vpon him fell: he no where doth appeare,
Fell from high Princes courts, or Ladies bowres,
As when a greedie Wolfe through hunger fell
Thereby so fearelesse, and so fell he grew,
The Antelope, and Wolfe both fierce and fell;
With dying fit, that downe she fell for paine.
Therewith they gan, both furious and fell,
So long they fight, and fell reuenge pursue,
She fell to ground for sorrowfull regret,
Then downe againe she fell vnto the ground;
For this young Prince, when first to armes he fell;
So downe he fell before the cruell beast,
Whom great Orgoglio with his puissaunce fell
With furious force, and indignation fell;
But forward fare, as their aduentures fell,
And euer ready for your foeman fell.
Through which into his darke abisse all rauin fell.
With which he stroke so furious and so fell,
Vpon his crest the hardned yron fell,
Into the same the knight backe ouerthrowen, fell.
Aboue his wonted pitch, with countenance fell,
Wherein he fell, or sharper edge did feele,
And downe he fell, with dread of shame sore terrifide.
And daintie deare, which on the ground still fell,
Into that same he fell: which did from death him saue.
So downe he fell, and forth his life did breath,
So downe he fell, that th'earth him vnderneath
So downe he fell, as an huge rockie clift,
So downe he fell, and like an heaped mountaine lay.
And fell intent ye did at earst me meet;
Where he abode, themselues at discord fell,
With horrible assault, and furie fell,
Or fell Erinnys, in your noble harts
And ayme at him, fell flat to ground for feare,
Downe fell to ground, and crept into a bush,
Against him turning all his fell intent,
And I pursewing my fell purpose, after went.
Griefe is a flood, and loue a monster fell;
With his bright blade did smite at him so fell,
On his broad shield, bit not, but glauncing fell
Their fell contention still increased more,
He then vprose, inflam'd with fell despight,
Readie to drowne himselfe for fell despight.
Yet was the force so furious and so fell,
He groueling fell, all gored in his gushing wound.
By whose aduise old Priams cittie fell,
Into the which returning backe, he fell:
And fell to vaine voluptuous disease:
With bloud of Henalois, which therein fell.
The reach of men, through flight into fond mischief fell.
Made warre on him, and fell him selfe in fight:
Which fled a sunder, and him fell before,
But to the ground the idle quarrell fell:
Vpon him fell, and lode vpon him layd;
Becomes more fell, and all that him withstands
That groueling to the ground he fell, and fild his place.
But his dead corse vpon the flore fell nathemore.
Had them enraged with fell surquedry;
The which into an ample lauer fell,
But Guyon droue so furious and fell,
Nigh a speares length behind his crouper fell,
Full of great enuie and fell gealosy,
But fierce Bacchante seemd too fell and keene;
Some fell to daunce, some fell to hazardry,
Some fell to daunce, some fell to hazardry,
And fell intent against the virgin sheene:
Mongst which it fell into that Faeries mind,
Returned home, the royall Infant fell
Like a swift Otter, fell through emptinesse,
The fruitfull plaines, and with fell cruelty,
At last their wayes so fell, that they mote part
So fell proud Marinell vpon the pretious shore.
With so fell force and villeinous despighte,
To him he turned, and with rigour fell
Downe on the ground his carkas groueling fell;
And glauncing fell to ground, but him annoyed naught.
But th'head fell backeward on the continent.
That from his steed he fell in deadly swowne;
Vpon her fell all naked bare displayd;
Without fell rancor, or fond gealosie;
Into misfortune fell, as ye did heare,
And with fell looke and hollow deadly gaze
The quarrey throwes to ground with fell despight,
And how he fell into that Gyaunts hands,
Which with the Prince of Darknesse fell somewhile,
Fell streight to ground in great astonishment;
What to Aeneas fell; sith that men sayne
So forth he rode, as his aduenture fell;
The old man could not fly, but fell to ground halfe ded.
When wearie of their sport to sleepe they fell,
That on the rockes he fell so flit and light,
Vntroubled of vile feare, or bitter fell.
That with fell woodnesse he effierced was,
And turning to her selfe his fell intent,
He fell halfe dead; next stroke him should haue slaine,
Fell softly forth, as of his owne accord,
And perfect hole, prostrate she fell vnto the ground.
Before faire Britomart, she fell prostrate,
That vnder great Alcides furie fell:
The noble Argonauts to outrage fell:
So fell those two in spight of both their prydes,
Did beare them both to fell auenges end,
They stemme ech other with so fell despight,
Haue rays'd this cruell warre and outrage fell,
Yet from the wound no drop of bloud there fell,
His haughtie courage to aduengement fell:
And so gaue way vnto his fell intent:
Till feeling life to fayle, it fell, and deadly slept.
So thicke they fell, and forcibly were sent,
That downe he fell as dead in all mens sight:
So both at once fell dead vpon the field,
Their wrathfull blades downe fell out of their hand,
And friends profest are chaungd to foemen fell:
So much more sorely to the ground he fell,
And as it fell, his steed he ready found.
By that the gloomy euening on them fell,
And rudely tumbling downe vnder his horse feete fell.
And fell away, as feeling secret blame.
Shall else be told in order, as it fell.
Had fild, that he to fell reueng was fully bent.
Vpon them fell, before her timely howre;
For fell despight, and gnaw his gealous hart,
With so fell rage, her selfe she lightly gan
With such fell greedines he her assayled,
Till on her horses hinder parts it fell;
Fell downe to ground, as if the steele had sence,
At last fell humbly downe vpon his knee,
With fell intent, on him to bene ywroke,
Her hand fell downe, and would no longer hold
She almost fell againe into a swound,
With fell despight her cruell arrowes tynde
For on a day, by fortune as it fell,
Like as it fell to this vnhappy boy,
There she alighting, fell before her feet,
He her beholding, at her feet downe fell,
To which they drew, ere night vpon them fell;
Nathlesse it fell with so despiteous dreare
So as it fell there was a gentle Squire,
Sixe they were all, all full of fell despight,
Vpon the sea to wreake his fell intent;
Cause of their discord, and so fell debate,
Of Ate and Duessa they fell out,
Of fell reuenge, in their malicious mood
For till the world from his perfection fell
It bit the earth for very fell despight,
As fortune fell; yet litle lost or wonne:
Your misery, how fell ye in this state.
Like a fell Lionesse at him she flew,
Soone after eke came she, with fell intent,
And at her strooke with puissance fearefull fell;
That downe she fell vpon the grassie field,
Through slipperie footing, fell into the brooke,
For very fell despight, which she conceiued,
But kicks, and squals, and shriekes for fell despight:
The fell contagion may thereof restraine,
At last proud Radigund with fell despight,
That with most fell despight and deadly hate,
With flesh of men, whom through fell tyranny
Or fell Medea, when on Colchicke strand
Is so exceeding furious and fell,
That like a stone it fell vpon the land,
Now at that instant, as occasion fell,
But this fell Tyrant, through his tortious powre,
Who after that his monstrous father fell
Fell straight about their neckes, as they did kneele,
That downe he fell vppon his mother deare,
He brayd aloud for very fell despight;
Downe streight to ground fell his astonisht steed,
Like a fell mastiffe through enraging heat,
That all the three attonce fell on the plaine:
Full of fell rauin and fierce greedinesse;
Then downe to ground fell that deformed Masse,
A ship all readie (as good fortune fell)
With dreadfull terror, and with fell intent;
With bitter rage and fell contention,
To Faery Court, where what him fell shall else be told.
And fell Chimï¿½ra in her darkesome den,
With so fell fury, and dispiteous forse,
And forth at last did breake in speaches sharpe and fell.
Then North; then neither, but as fortune fell.
For fell despight, to be so sorely crost;
She fell into that saluage villaines hand,
Like a fell Lion at him fiercely flew,
Vpon them two they fell with might and maine,
And beat them back, whilest many vnderneath him fell.
He woxe nigh mad with wrath and fell despight,
Turnes him about with fell auengement;
That to the ground he fell in senselesse swone:
Ne secretly from thought of fell reuenge surceasse.
And scattered all about, fell on the flowre.
Perdie (said he) in euill houre it fell,
Like a fell Lyon leaped to him light,
Fell flat to ground, ne word vnto him sayd,
To whom foule Infamie, and fell Despight
Fell into wretched woes, which she repented late.
That for her sake fell into misery:
He in his necke had set his foote with fell disdaine.
But fell to ground, like to a lumpe of durt;
When first the gentle Squire at variaunce fell
Of sundry things, as fell, to worke delay;
And supper readie dight, they to it fell
They fell to daunce: then did they all agree,
All saue the shepheard, who for fell despight
That with fell clawes full of fierce gourmandize,
That to the ground astonished he fell;
Lanc't through the arme, fell down with him in drerie swound.
Of carcases, which dying on her fell.
To stay their cruell hands from slaughter fell.
That euen his hart for very fell despight,
Fell all at ods, and fought through fury fierce and bold.
She vnto him recounted, all that fell:
That made him almost mad for fell despight.
Those two were foes the fellonest on ground,
Of PhÃ¦dria, thine owne fellow seruaunt;
But euery one did striue his fellow downe to throw.
To be her thrall, his fellow seruant vild;
For pitie that ye want a fellow for your ayd.
His other fellow Pagan, which before him past.
Whose fellow he before had sent apart;
Fellow of this I beare, throwne not in vaine,
Who when on ground they saw their fellow slaine,
Where when he saw his fellow lifelesse ly,
How both he and his fellow there in place
Each gan his fellow solace and embrace,
Sixe of thy fellowes of the best array,
Whom when his other fellowes saw, they fled
Whose fellowship seemd far vnfit for warlike swaine.
And of their louely fellowship full glade,
With that a ioyous fellowship issewd
Was to that goodly fellowship restor'd,
Now falne into their fellowship by chance,
For glorie vaine their fellowship to lose,
To seeke by flight her fellowship t'eschew,
That by his fellowship, he colour might
And felly gnarre, vntill dayes enemy
In flaming Phlegeton does not so felly roste.
His Beast he felly prickt on either syde,
And charging him a fresh thus felly him bespake.
Yet he therewith so felly still did raue,
Like as a curre doth felly bite and teare
Fortune enuying good, hath felly frowned,
So both together ylike felly bent,
Whom when the Prince so felly saw to rage,
And with their litle stings right felly fare;
For very felnesse lowd he gan to weepe,
Gnawing her nayles for felnesse and for yre,
The felnesse of her heart, right fully bent
Her flesh for felnesse, which she inward hid:
And with more eager felnesse him pursew'd:
Where Archimago said a felon strong
And to him said, Now felon sure I read,
And freely read, what wicked felon so
The whiles the cursed felon high did reare
And did acquite a murdrer felonous;
Which forth he sent with felonous despight,
Twixt inward doole and felonous despight;
But to himselfe his felonous intent
But bit his lip for felonous despight,
Abhorred bloudshed, and vile felony,
And for his sake haue felt full many an heauie stowre.
His chaunged powres at first them selues not felt,
Haue felt the bitter dint of his auenging blade.
Which when he knew, and felt ourfeeble harts
For neuer felt his imperceable brest
Proceeded, yet each one felt secretly
Which when he felt to moue, he hoped faire
And when he felt the folly of his Lord,
Soone as Occasion felt her selfe vntyde,
When as againe he armed felt his hond;
That had not yet felt Cupides wanton rage,
That neuer tasted grace, nor goodnesse felt,
Tho when he felt him dead, a downe he kest
Yet life he saw, and felt his mightie maine,
She softly felt, if any member mooued,
Such secret ease felt gentle Britomart,
When feeble nature felt her selfe opprest,
She softly felt, and rubbed busily,
Which all that while she felt to pant and quake,
He had him seene, and felt the crueltie
And felt in his old courage new delight
Then for the burning torment, which he felt,
Had felt the point of his hart-percing dart,
As if no sorrow she ne felt ne drad;
Tho when she felt her selfe to be vnbound,
No word they spake, nor earthly thing they felt,
They felt, could once sustaine the hideous stowre,
With double life, and griefe, which when he felt,
Ne felt his blood to wast, ne powres emperisht,
When all vnwares he felt an hideous sway
He felt his hart for very paine to quake,
And felt some ruth, or sence his hand did lacke,
Whilest he in armes her bore; but when she felt
His stubborne heart, that neuer felt misfare
And feeble spirit inly felt refection;
But when he felt him shrinke, and come to ward,
When once he felt his foeman to relent;
Now wanting them he felt himselfe so light,
A doubtfull sense of things, not so well seene, as felt.
And wondrous ioy felt in her spirits thrall:
Had neuer ioyance felt, nor chearefull thought,
In perfect forme, as this good Lady felt,
And partly female of his fruitfull seed;
Both male and female, both vnder one name:
For as the sister did in feminine
And trained vp in true feminitee:
A monstrous beast ybred in filthy fen
And flying fast as Roebucke through the fen,
Where he was fostred long in Stygian fen,
Yet was the fence thereof but weake and thin;
Out of the fennes of Allan do arise,
That to those fennes for fastnesse she did fly,
And all so faire, and fensible withall,
No fort so fensible, no wals so strong,
And fenst himselfe about with many a flaming brand.
Through mischieuous debate, and deadly feood,
Great liking vnto many, but true loue to feowe.
Charmd or enchaunted (answerd he then ferce)
But faire Charissa to a louely fere
And Cambel tooke Cambina to his fere,
But some fayre Franion, fit for such a fere,
Then shalt thou take him to thy loued fere,
To take Briana for his louing fere,
That none she worthie thought to be her fere,
By all meanes shund to match with any forrein fere.
Haue trayned bene with many noble feres
Out of her fleshly ferme fled to the place of paine.
Which when the noble Ferramont espide,
With which so sore he Ferramont assaid,
Then did Sir Ferramont vnto them shew
Which Ferrau late from Braggadochio wonne,
It was to weete the bold Sir Ferraugh hight,
Stout Ferrex and sterne Porrex him in prison threw.
And him to ferrie ouer that deepe ford:
The Ferriman, as Alma had behight,
Her ferry brought, where him she byding fond,
To ferry that old man ouer the perlous foord.
Did ferry him ouer the Idle lake:
So forth they rowed, and that Ferryman
That may not be, said then the Ferryman
His fattie waues do fertile slime outwell,
It was a chosen plot of fertile land,
With suddein fury all the fertile plaine,
